STORYLINE
Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan met Chinese President Hu Jintao in Beijing on Tuesday during an official visit to boost business and political ties between the two rising economic powers, despite differences over Syria and China\'s ethnic Uighur region.
Later, Erdogan met Chinese Vice President Xi Jinping.
The official Xinhua News Agency said Erdogan brought a delegation of 300 businessmen, seeking more Chinese investment in Turkey and an increase in Turkish exports.
The visit is the first to China in 27 years by a Turkish premier and follows a February trip by Xi to Ankara and Istanbul, where the countries signed deals worth (b) billions of dollars.
China\'s Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Erdogan first stopped in Urumqi, capital of the far west Xinjiang region, on Sunday. Xinjiang is home to China\'s Uighurs, who are ethnically related to Turks.
Ethnic tensions have led to violence in the region in recent years, and relations between the countries dipped in 2009 when renewed violence broke out in Xinjiang and Erdogan described China\'s use of overwhelming force against anti-government protesters as a type of genocide.
